---

<DefaultLayout
  title="Programs by Province — Interactive Map — FirstHomeGuide.ca"
  description="Explore an interactive map of Canada to find every federal and provincial first-time home buyer program you qualify for. Province-specific incentives, rebates, and savings."
>
  <section class="pt-8 md:pt-12 lg:pt-16 pb-0">
    <div class="container max-w-screen-xl">
      <a
        href="/tools"
        class="text-muted-foreground hover:text-foreground mb-2 inline-flex items-center gap-1 text-sm transition-colors"
      >
        &larr; All Tools
      </a>
    </div>
  </section>

  <CanadaMapExplorer client:load />

  <section class="section-padding pt-8 pb-0">
    <div class="container max-w-screen-xl">
      <div class="prose prose-neutral dark:prose-invert max-w-none">
        <h2>First-Time Home Buyer Programs Across Canada</h2>
        <p>Canada offers generous federal programs available to first-time buyers in every province, along with province-specific incentives that vary significantly depending on where you purchase. By understanding and stacking these programs together, you can save anywhere from $15,000 to $45,000 or more on your first home purchase. The key is knowing what exists and applying for everything you qualify for before or during your purchase.</p>

        <h3>Federal Programs Available in Every Province</h3>
        <p>The federal government provides several programs designed specifically for first-time home buyers, and these are available regardless of which province or territory you live in.</p>
        <p>The <a href="https://www.canada.ca/en/revenue-agency/services/tax/individuals/topics/first-home-savings-account.html" target="_blank" rel="nofollow noopener noreferrer">First Home Savings Account (FHSA)</a> allows you to contribute up to $8,000 per year, to a lifetime maximum of $40,000. Contributions are tax-deductible like an RRSP, and withdrawals for a qualifying home purchase are completely tax-free — making it one of the most powerful savings vehicles available to Canadian buyers.</p>
        <p>The <a href="https://www.canada.ca/en/revenue-agency/services/tax/individuals/topics/rrsps-related-plans/what-home-buyers-plan.html" target="_blank" rel="nofollow noopener noreferrer">Home Buyers' Plan (HBP)</a> lets you withdraw up to $60,000 per person from your RRSPs to put toward a down payment, interest-free. If you are buying with a partner who also qualifies, that is up to $120,000 combined. You repay the amount over 15 years, starting the second year after your withdrawal.</p>
        <p>The <a href="https://www.canada.ca/en/revenue-agency/services/tax/individuals/topics/about-your-tax-return/tax-return/completing-a-tax-return/deductions-credits-expenses/line-31270-home-buyers-amount.html" target="_blank" rel="nofollow noopener noreferrer">Home Buyers' Tax Credit (HBTC)</a> provides a $1,500 non-refundable tax credit that you claim on your tax return for the year you purchase your home. Additionally, if you are buying a newly constructed home, you may qualify for the GST/HST New Housing Rebate, which can return a portion of the sales tax paid on the purchase.</p>

        <h3>How Provincial Programs Vary</h3>
        <p>Provincial programs differ widely, and they can add up to significant savings depending on where you buy. In Ontario, first-time buyers receive a land transfer tax rebate of up to $4,000, and those purchasing in Toronto can claim an additional Municipal Land Transfer Tax rebate of up to $4,475. British Columbia offers a full property transfer tax exemption on homes valued at $500,000 or less, with a partial exemption on homes up to $835,000.</p>
        <p>Alberta stands out because it has no provincial land transfer tax at all, which saves buyers thousands of dollars compared to other provinces. In Quebec, the city of Montreal offers grants of up to $15,000 for first-time buyers purchasing within the city. Maritime provinces provide various rebates and down payment assistance programs tailored to their local markets. For a comprehensive overview of what is available, the <a href="https://www.cmhc-schl.gc.ca/consumers/home-buying" target="_blank" rel="nofollow noopener noreferrer">CMHC homebuying guide</a> is an excellent starting point.</p>

        <h3>Stacking Programs for Maximum Savings</h3>
        <p>The real power comes from combining multiple programs on a single purchase. Consider an Ontario buyer purchasing a $500,000 home: they could use $40,000 from their FHSA for part of the down payment (tax-free), withdraw $60,000 from their RRSP through the HBP (interest-free), claim the $1,500 HBTC on their tax return, and receive the Ontario land transfer tax rebate of $4,000. That is a combined benefit of over $105,000 in tax-advantaged funds and savings applied to a single transaction.</p>

        <h3>Can I use all these programs at once?</h3>
        <p>Yes. Federal programs such as the FHSA, HBP, and HBTC are designed to stack with each other and with provincial programs. There is no rule preventing you from claiming every program you are eligible for on the same purchase. The only requirement is that you meet the individual eligibility criteria for each program, which typically means being a first-time home buyer as defined by each program and using the home as your primary residence.</p>

        <h3>Do programs change depending on where I live?</h3>
        <p>Federal programs are identical across Canada — every qualifying first-time buyer has access to the FHSA, HBP, and HBTC regardless of province. Provincial programs, however, vary significantly. Some provinces offer land transfer tax rebates, others provide direct grants, and some — like Alberta — have no land transfer tax at all, which is itself a form of savings. It is worth researching the specific programs available in the province where you plan to buy, as the differences can amount to thousands of dollars.</p>
      </div>
    </div>
  </section>

